<h2>How to Write a Press Release That Gets Published</h2>
<p>Submitting to 173 sites means nothing if your press release is poorly written. Editors reject 90% of submissions for the same reasons.</p>
<h3>Press Release Format That Works</h3>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Element</th>
<th>Rule</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Headline</td>
<td>Under 80 characters. Include the news. No clickbait.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Subheadline</td>
<td>One sentence expanding the headline. Optional.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Dateline</td>
<td>City, State. Date format. Always include.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Lead paragraph</td>
<td>Who, what, when, where, why in 30 words or less.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Body</td>
<td>300-500 words total. Quotes from a named source.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Boilerplate</td>
<td>50-word company description. Same across all releases.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Contact info</td>
<td>Name, email, phone. Real person, not a generic inbox.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<h3>Submission Checklist</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Press release follows AP style formatting</li>
<li>[ ] Headline includes the actual news (not hype)</li>
<li>[ ] Lead paragraph answers who, what, when, where, why</li>
<li>[ ] Body stays under 500 words</li>
<li>[ ] Includes one direct quote from a named spokesperson</li>
<li>[ ] Boilerplate company description is consistent across all submissions</li>
<li>[ ] Links point to specific landing pages, not just the homepage</li>
<li>[ ] No jargon, buzzwords, or promotional language</li>
<li>[ ] Contact information includes a real person's name and email</li>
</ul>
